WEBVTT

00:07.383 --> 00:09.465
(PHONE RINGING)

00:09.552 --> 00:11.793
-(CHATTER)
-(MACH|NE WHIRRING)

00:22.440 --> 00:24.852
Girl, is it me or is that clock
moving extremely slow today?

00:24.942 --> 00:26.682
-DESIREE: A couple more hours.
-(CHUCKLES)

00:26.777 --> 00:28.768
-(CELL PHONE BUZZING)
-Your phone ringing.

00:35.119 --> 00:37.235
Hey, Neecee.

00:37.330 --> 00:38.991
What is it?

00:39.916 --> 00:41.247
Shit!

00:41.334 --> 00:44.826
Tell 'em not to touch anything.
I'm on my way. Tell 'em that.

00:44.921 --> 00:46.912
Tell 'em to stop, God damn it.

00:51.010 --> 00:53.752
(CUPID SHUFFLE PLAYING)

01:08.319 --> 01:09.308
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

01:12.156 --> 01:14.898
Hold on. Hold on.

01:29.924 --> 01:32.916
-Wrong way.
-This way, this way.

01:46.357 --> 01:50.270
I'm so sorry, baby.
I told them, but they wouldn't listen.

01:50.361 --> 01:52.272
(METAL CREAKING)

01:57.952 --> 01:59.613
Motherfuckers.

02:11.716 --> 02:13.957
ANTOINE: Desiree, I'm gonna
call you back after class, all right?

02:14.051 --> 02:17.339
They did it, Antoine. They fuckin' did it.

02:17.805 --> 02:20.968
What? What are you talking about?

02:21.058 --> 02:24.425
Mama's house, they tore it down.

02:24.520 --> 02:26.056
What?

02:26.147 --> 02:28.138
(WOOD CRUNCHING)

04:04.328 --> 04:06.319
(BAND PLAYING JAZZ)

05:04.263 --> 05:08.427
-(AUD|ENCE APPLAUDING)
-Yeahl

05:08.517 --> 05:10.303
-(LAUGH|NG)
-Yeah.

05:10.394 --> 05:11.383
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.

05:11.479 --> 05:14.721
That was an original piece
by Leon "Kid Chocolate" Brown

05:14.815 --> 05:16.806
called Little Big Chief.

05:16.901 --> 05:20.314
This next one's by New Orleans' own
Jon Batiste, home for the holidays.

05:20.404 --> 05:21.940
Ladies and gentlemen, give it up for him.

05:22.031 --> 05:24.738
Yeah, you're right.

05:24.825 --> 05:25.940
Yeah!

05:27.328 --> 05:30.035
Always a pleasure
to be playing with these fellas again.

05:30.122 --> 05:32.499
This next one is called
Calm Before the Storm.

05:32.583 --> 05:34.198
Enjoy.

05:34.460 --> 05:35.950
(BAND PLAYING)

05:45.554 --> 05:47.840
(FRIDGE DOOR OPENS)

05:48.057 --> 05:49.046
(FRIDGE DOOR CLOSES)

05:50.601 --> 05:52.592
(ANTOINE GRUNTS)

06:02.947 --> 06:04.903
-She's asleep?
-Uh-huh.

06:14.542 --> 06:16.624
I got a gig at the Hall tomorrow.

06:17.545 --> 06:19.957
-You wanna come?
-I don't know.

06:20.089 --> 06:21.829
We'll see.

06:21.924 --> 06:24.006
Take your mind off your troubles.

06:24.093 --> 06:25.833
I doubt it.

06:31.517 --> 06:34.600
You find out what happened?

06:34.687 --> 06:37.144
Must have talked to five different officers.

06:37.231 --> 06:40.314
Nobody could tell me
how it could be on the NOAH list to be...

06:40.401 --> 06:42.266
-What you call it?
-Remediated.

06:42.361 --> 06:43.350
Uh-huh.

06:43.654 --> 06:47.317
And on the "to-be-demolished" list
at the same time.

06:48.951 --> 06:50.566
Well, you still own the lot.

06:50.661 --> 06:53.903
For what that's worth.
Who's gonna buy it, anyway?

06:53.998 --> 06:57.616
All that vacant land down there
look like the country.

06:58.127 --> 06:59.867
Well, true that.

07:04.800 --> 07:06.006
You tell your mama yet?

07:10.598 --> 07:12.338
(SIGHS)

07:14.810 --> 07:18.018
(CHATTER)

07:22.693 --> 07:24.604
-All right?
-You all right?

07:24.695 --> 07:26.185
-Delmond.
-Hey, good to see you again.

07:26.280 --> 07:27.941
-Great set. Beautiful.
-Thank you.

07:28.032 --> 07:28.987
Let me introduce you.

07:29.074 --> 07:31.110
-Yates Healey.
-How are you doing?

07:31.201 --> 07:33.112
-C.J. Liguori.
-I don't think we've met.

07:33.203 --> 07:34.864
-Great set.
-Thank you, thank you. Appreciate it.

07:34.955 --> 07:37.162
I thought I detected
a little Lee Morgan in there.

07:37.958 --> 07:40.540
Yeah, I basically grew up
with The Sidewinder.

07:40.628 --> 07:42.619
My tastes are a little previous to that.

07:42.713 --> 07:44.203
Jabbo Smith, "Muggsy" Spanier.

07:44.465 --> 07:47.457
-Ain't nothing wrong with that.
-l'm more Tom Browne myself.

07:48.719 --> 07:52.712
We keep him around for his
architectural skills, not his musical tastes.

07:52.806 --> 07:56.219
You all are involved
with the National Jazz Center thing.

07:56.310 --> 07:59.643
Yeah. Any chance
we can get together after the holidays?

07:59.730 --> 08:02.813
-I don't see why not.
-LIGUORI: Great.

08:05.611 --> 08:11.572
(SINGING)
It takes a Dominicker hen to enjoy the sun

08:13.827 --> 08:19.697
It takes a Dominicker hen to enjoy the sun

08:22.127 --> 08:25.961
Take a Shanghai rooster

08:31.970 --> 08:35.588
(YODELING)

08:35.724 --> 08:37.430
Thanks.

08:50.948 --> 08:52.108
EVERETT: Same message I left yesterday.

08:52.199 --> 08:56.158
I need to talk to Dr. Cataldi
about the Henry Glover case.

08:57.538 --> 09:00.371
Glover, Henry.

09:04.461 --> 09:07.373
Right. I'm also trying to get a roster

09:07.464 --> 09:11.207
of all the forensic pathologists
who were at DMORT after the storm,

09:11.301 --> 09:14.464
especially the ones who were out of state.

09:16.807 --> 09:18.013
Orleans.

09:22.396 --> 09:25.388
I've already had multiple conversations
with Dr. Minyard's office,

09:25.482 --> 09:29.646
and they told me to call the State,
which is why I've been calling you.

09:36.493 --> 09:37.994
All right.

09:38.078 --> 09:39.784
Thank you.

09:43.417 --> 09:45.408
This is some life legacy here.

09:45.502 --> 09:48.915
Tootie made 52 suits.

09:49.006 --> 09:51.998
Man, I'm just trying to get it together for one.

09:52.092 --> 09:54.583
It's a lot to live up to.

09:56.013 --> 09:57.503
Tell me about it.

10:01.268 --> 10:03.759
This is his last suit.

10:04.438 --> 10:06.770
-He was the prettiest, no doubt.
-DAV|S: The family home

10:06.857 --> 10:10.941
of Allison "Tootie" Montana,
Big Chief of the Yellow Pocahontas.

10:11.028 --> 10:12.609
JOYCE: What's going on out there?

10:12.696 --> 10:15.688
DAVIS: Three-dimensional
downtown Mardi Gras lndian suits.

10:16.283 --> 10:18.274
Now, he had a...

10:21.455 --> 10:23.537
What? Ladies and gentlemen,

10:23.624 --> 10:27.537
we are witnessing the rare confluence
of two seminal New Orleans traditions.

10:27.628 --> 10:31.541
The quiet power behind
the Yellow Pocahontas, Miss Joyce Montana,

10:31.632 --> 10:33.793
her son, Big Chief Darryl Montana.

10:33.884 --> 10:36.796
Also, Delmond Lambreaux,

10:37.471 --> 10:42.511
modern jazz trumpeter par excellence,
also, son of Big Chief Albert Lambreaux.

10:42.601 --> 10:43.886
Guardians of the Flame.

10:43.977 --> 10:45.558
DJ Davis.

10:45.646 --> 10:47.056
WWOZ.

10:47.147 --> 10:48.978
Love the new album with your dad.

10:49.066 --> 10:50.647
-Thanks, brah.
-lt's great.

10:50.734 --> 10:51.974
What's going on?

10:52.069 --> 10:54.060
McAlary's Musical Heritage Tours.

10:54.154 --> 10:56.645
We're doing a whole spin
around the 7th Ward.

10:56.740 --> 10:58.731
Don't get many tourists around here.

10:58.826 --> 11:00.407
-Exact...
-(CROWD CHUCKLES)

11:00.494 --> 11:02.075
What did I say? Exactly.

11:02.162 --> 11:04.744
Yeah, we'd just swing by,
pay our respects to your family,

11:04.832 --> 11:07.164
wander across to Perseverance Hall,

11:07.251 --> 11:10.243
and then check out Sidney Bechet's house
while it's still standing.

11:10.337 --> 11:11.668
Sidney Bechet's house is around here?

11:11.755 --> 11:14.337
Around the "cornder," Marais Street.

11:14.424 --> 11:16.756
Do you care to join us?

11:16.885 --> 11:19.342
Sidney Bechet's house? Desitively.

11:19.429 --> 11:20.418
Great!

11:20.514 --> 11:22.880
-(CLATTER|NG)
-TlM: So, how was Cochon?

11:22.975 --> 11:25.512
WOMAN: Okay. Like, crazy busy all the time.

11:25.602 --> 11:28.059
TIM: Well, we hope to be crazy busy here, too.

11:28.438 --> 11:29.974
Tim?

11:31.191 --> 11:32.601
Excuse me.

11:36.697 --> 11:39.905
Aren't you worried? Because we can't...

11:39.992 --> 11:44.031
I mean, you're not even considering the
possibility of opening without liquor, right?

11:44.121 --> 11:46.863
-(LAUGHS) That'd be lethal.
-Lethal. I agree.

11:46.957 --> 11:48.493
Now, don't sweat the small stuff, Chef.

11:48.584 --> 11:50.700
I told you. That's what I'm here for.

11:51.503 --> 11:54.711
-Liquor license is not small stuff, Tim.
-lt'll be there.

11:54.798 --> 11:56.959
I spoke to the lawyer this morning.

11:57.050 --> 12:00.588
You worry about the kitchen, Chef.
I'll take care of this out here.

12:04.391 --> 12:07.303
TIM: I think you'd be a great fit
if you're interested.

12:07.644 --> 12:09.225
Definitely.

12:09.605 --> 12:10.640
TIM: Terrific.

12:13.150 --> 12:17.814
Okay, so, between 1900 and 1907,

12:17.905 --> 12:21.648
Charles "Buddy" Bolden
basically invented jazz.

12:21.742 --> 12:24.984
Before Jelly Roll Morton or after?

12:25.078 --> 12:26.409
-You know... (SIGHS)
-(LAUGHING)

12:26.496 --> 12:27.872
All right...

12:29.166 --> 12:33.159
This building here, Perseverance Hall,
built in the 1880s,

12:33.253 --> 12:37.997
is one of two places left where we
actually know that Buddy Bolden played.

12:38.091 --> 12:41.504
I'm confused.
Is this the same as Preservation Hall?

12:41.595 --> 12:43.176
Nope. That's in the Quarter.

12:43.263 --> 12:44.252
Told you.

12:44.348 --> 12:48.762
-How much of this was due to Katrina?
-This place was a wreck before the storm.

12:48.852 --> 12:50.934
In Chicago, Lincoln Gardens,

12:51.021 --> 12:54.684
The Arcadia, pretty much
all of the buildings on the Stroll,

12:54.775 --> 12:57.266
I mean, they met the wrecking ball years ago.

12:57.361 --> 13:01.775
Well, you know, Chicago, New York,
it's all about the future, you know?

13:01.865 --> 13:04.402
Tear down, rebuild. Tear down, rebuild.

13:06.036 --> 13:07.617
This is New Orleans.

13:07.704 --> 13:08.955
(ROOSTER CROWS)

13:09.039 --> 13:12.748
We just let it go to hell.

13:13.293 --> 13:15.500
Preservation through neglect.

13:19.967 --> 13:23.004
They said he'd get back to me tomorrow.

13:23.095 --> 13:24.505
Manana.

13:24.596 --> 13:28.635
Manana doesn't really mean tomorrow.
Itjust means not today.

13:28.725 --> 13:30.761
I'm starting to understand that.

13:30.852 --> 13:33.309
Cataldi might not have
the answers you're looking for anyway.

13:33.772 --> 13:34.978
Why not?

13:35.065 --> 13:37.852
The State didn't keep
very good records after the storm.

13:37.943 --> 13:39.524
People came down here to help.

13:39.987 --> 13:42.649
There were thousands of volunteers
from every corner of the country.

13:42.739 --> 13:43.694
It was chaos.

13:43.782 --> 13:46.819
Yeah, but not thousands
of forensic pathologists.

13:46.910 --> 13:49.401
No. Dozens maybe.

13:51.081 --> 13:54.244
That's the size list we could cold-call,
if we had it.

13:54.960 --> 13:59.078
Is there a way to compile one,
you know, state by state?

13:59.256 --> 14:01.588
Maybe their public health people
kept records.

14:01.675 --> 14:02.664
Mmm-mmm.

14:04.928 --> 14:06.384
Local papers.

14:07.597 --> 14:11.966
If some forensic pathologist in Scranton
volunteered at DMORT for a few days,

14:12.060 --> 14:15.518
it might not be a big deal down here,
but in Scranton...

14:15.689 --> 14:17.099
Front page news.

14:17.441 --> 14:19.147
Page three of the Living section anyway.

14:19.276 --> 14:20.732
(BOTH LAUGH)

14:20.861 --> 14:24.319
-(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)
-Oh, my God, thank you so much.

14:24.406 --> 14:27.443
I mean, really? It's definite?
I can tell the boys?

14:29.786 --> 14:33.574
I don't even know what to say. I don't...

14:36.585 --> 14:40.498
Okay, all right. Well, Merry Christmas, Marvin.

14:43.300 --> 14:45.416
Okay. All right.

14:45.510 --> 14:48.923
-Great tour today! You will not believe...
-Okay, Iwill.

14:49.014 --> 14:51.005
-...who I ran into.
-I will. Okay, bye.

14:52.476 --> 14:56.060
-"Yeah, I will." "I will," what? Who was that?
-It was Marvin.

14:56.146 --> 14:58.808
-He had some good news.
-(MUSIC STOPS)

14:59.733 --> 15:01.143
Who did you run into?

15:01.234 --> 15:04.692
Joyce and Darryl Montana,
and Delmond Lambreaux.

15:05.030 --> 15:07.146
(HIP HOP MUSIC BLARING)

15:07.240 --> 15:10.778
-Davis, what the fuck?
-Sess 4-5.

15:10.869 --> 15:13.827
Dropped it off last night at '02.
It's brand-new.

15:14.164 --> 15:17.406
-It's a rallying cry to stop...
-No. Shoes.

15:17.501 --> 15:18.786
-What?
-Shoes, off.

15:18.877 --> 15:20.037
-What? I gotta pee.
-Shoes!

15:20.128 --> 15:22.585
It's a rallying cry to stop the demolition.

15:22.672 --> 15:25.755
-What demolition?
-The projects, the big four.

15:25.884 --> 15:29.251
There's 4,500 units of low-income housing.

15:29.387 --> 15:31.093
The city's gonna vote on it tomorrow.

15:31.181 --> 15:33.923
-Right, right. Okay. So, Davis...
-No, Annie.

15:34.017 --> 15:38.556
It has been my experience that
parents respond more to cool indifference

15:38.647 --> 15:41.935
than desperate attempts to please.

15:42.025 --> 15:43.185
Yeah, well, you would know.

15:43.902 --> 15:45.608
They're not staying here, are they?

15:45.695 --> 15:49.734
-Relax. They're at The Columns.
-Fuck. Perfect. They'll really like that place.

15:49.825 --> 15:51.440
Yeah, but you don't know my mother.

15:51.535 --> 15:56.529
I mean, she'll find some excuse to drop by
and go over every surface with a white glove.

15:56.623 --> 15:57.612
What?

15:59.334 --> 16:01.165
Never mind.

16:03.004 --> 16:05.461
(LOUD MUSIC CONTINUES)

16:05.549 --> 16:07.380
I'll tell you later.

16:09.427 --> 16:10.883
(BLINKER TICKING)

16:38.206 --> 16:40.492
-(SIREN CHIRPS)
-Shit.

16:40.625 --> 16:42.911
(CHIRPING)

16:43.211 --> 16:45.122
(BLINKER TICKING)

16:50.010 --> 16:52.342
(TURNS OFF RADIO)

16:56.099 --> 16:57.930
(SIGHS)

17:02.522 --> 17:04.763
License and registration, please.

17:14.576 --> 17:18.535
You know why I pulled you over, miss?
You didn't use your turn signal back there.

17:18.622 --> 17:20.988
-But I did.
-(SNIFFS)

17:21.333 --> 17:23.995
What's that smell? Is that marijuana?

17:24.211 --> 17:26.998
-What?
-Step out of the vehicle, please.

17:27.797 --> 17:29.253
(SIGHS)

17:29.591 --> 17:31.707
(MELLOW JAZZ PLAYING)

17:31.801 --> 17:33.962
DELMOND: Me and Davina
are doing the cooking this year.

17:34.054 --> 17:36.010
(CHUCKUNG)

17:36.681 --> 17:38.217
You think we don't know how?

17:38.308 --> 17:40.390
Well, if Cheri was coming...

17:40.477 --> 17:41.887
What you mean "if Cheri was coming"?

17:41.978 --> 17:44.970
They're taking the kids
to Brian's folks this year.

17:45.065 --> 17:46.976
I thought they was definitely coming.

17:48.068 --> 17:50.855
Well, they ain't. I talked to her this morning.

17:52.489 --> 17:55.981
-You gonna eat something, Daddy?
-When I'm hungry.

17:58.787 --> 18:01.153
No, leave that. I'll get it. I'll get it.

18:01.248 --> 18:03.159
You get to your gig.

18:04.376 --> 18:07.743
Don't forget
you're my ride tomorrow morning.

18:08.046 --> 18:09.957
You're serious about that?

18:10.048 --> 18:12.915
Folks still wanting to come home
and all them buildings standing empty.

18:13.009 --> 18:15.421
Damn right I'm gonna be there.

18:15.512 --> 18:18.094
They've been wanting
to tear them projects down for years.

18:18.181 --> 18:21.344
Yeah, well, even a fool
can see what's happening.

18:21.518 --> 18:24.009
Public housing, Charity Hospital.

18:25.021 --> 18:28.104
Yeah, they've been
wanting to get rid of all of them.

18:28.316 --> 18:30.557
'Cause who's it benefit?

18:30.652 --> 18:32.768
Poor folks, black folks.

18:34.155 --> 18:36.362
You think I'd be running around town now,

18:36.449 --> 18:40.533
hat in hand, jumping through hoops,
trying to find a doctor if Charity was open?

18:41.246 --> 18:43.487
-Probably not.
-Well, then...

18:44.207 --> 18:46.869
They're trying to wash us away, son.

18:48.169 --> 18:50.706
What the storm and them broken levees
didn't finish...

18:50.797 --> 18:53.038
This is their golden opportunity.

18:54.551 --> 18:57.759
-You gonna get yourself arrested again?
-Nope.

18:58.555 --> 19:01.422
But I will make myself heard.

19:02.392 --> 19:03.723
No doubt.

19:16.281 --> 19:18.522
Cleanest car I've seen in a while.

19:18.908 --> 19:20.739
Who does your detailing?

19:22.078 --> 19:24.569
I guess I was mistaken about the smell, huh?

19:28.501 --> 19:31.243
You really should be more careful driving,
Miss Bernette.

19:32.172 --> 19:33.912
You have a good night, you hear?

19:45.143 --> 19:49.102
(BAND PLAYING)

19:59.282 --> 20:03.742
(SINGING)
Hey, my bucket got a hole in it

20:03.953 --> 20:08.071
Yeah, my bucket's got a hole in it

20:08.166 --> 20:12.375
Yeah, my bucket's got a hole in it

20:12.462 --> 20:16.375
Can't buy no beer

20:16.674 --> 20:21.043
Yeah, my bucket's got a hole in it

20:21.179 --> 20:25.889
I said my bucket's got a hole in it

20:25.975 --> 20:29.843
My bucket's got a hole in it

20:29.938 --> 20:33.522
I can't buy no beer

20:33.983 --> 20:37.350
I hear you knockin', but you can't come in

20:38.321 --> 20:41.939
I hear you knockin', but you can't come in

20:42.534 --> 20:46.197
I hear you knockin', but you can't come in

20:46.496 --> 20:49.909
You ain't got no beer

20:49.999 --> 20:51.990
Tell them something. Tell them something.

20:53.670 --> 20:55.410
Yeah, that's right.

21:03.513 --> 21:05.003
Yeah.

21:34.544 --> 21:36.205
(DRAWER CLOSES)

21:37.797 --> 21:40.584
That's over the line, even for you.

21:42.260 --> 21:46.219
If Wilson hasn't left a trail of fire behind him,
he's got nothing to worry about.

21:46.514 --> 21:48.379
Nobody will come fonIvard.

21:48.558 --> 21:51.641
And if he has,
wouldn't you want to know about it?

21:52.604 --> 21:55.721
-Has anyone come fonNard?
-What do you think?

21:57.775 --> 22:00.767
Either way,
this has nothing to do with my daughter.

22:01.946 --> 22:03.197
I came to you,

22:03.281 --> 22:08.150
instead of going to PIB and filing
a formal complaint against your officers.

22:08.244 --> 22:10.986
Thought you might want to
handle it in-house.

22:15.460 --> 22:19.373
Harassing my daughter.
That's not crossing a line for you?

22:24.010 --> 22:26.092
You'll look into it?

22:30.183 --> 22:32.014
I'll look into it.

22:36.606 --> 22:39.473
(MEN CHATTERING)

23:13.101 --> 23:15.217
-(GRUNTS)
-Hey, Daddy.

23:17.814 --> 23:19.179
What?

23:26.155 --> 23:28.567
Got a call from Cheri.

23:30.660 --> 23:34.744
Suddenly, Brian's people all right
with them not being there Christmas day.

23:38.001 --> 23:41.084
If I wanted them to know, I'd have told them.

23:42.171 --> 23:44.662
Your problems are our problems, Daddy.

23:47.844 --> 23:49.505
Davina know, too?

23:52.724 --> 23:54.840
(SIGHS) Damn, boy.

23:56.185 --> 23:59.677
She's just like her mother.
I'm not gonna get a minute's peace.

23:59.772 --> 24:03.014
-They needed to know.
-We're gonna be late.

24:14.704 --> 24:17.116
-FATHER: There she is.
-Hi.

24:17.290 --> 24:21.033
-Hi.
-Sweetheart, it's so wonderful to see you.

24:21.377 --> 24:24.665
-Hi. Dad.
-Hi, baby.

24:26.382 --> 24:28.634
Come, sit. Sit, sit, sit.

24:30.386 --> 24:33.048
-l'm sorry that I'm late.
-Not at all, sweetheart.

24:33.139 --> 24:35.130
-We just checked in.
-Yeah.

24:35.224 --> 24:37.601
-Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas.

24:37.894 --> 24:40.761
-So how was your flight?
-No complaints.

24:40.855 --> 24:41.970
Good.

24:42.065 --> 24:44.556
So, where's the boyfriend?

24:45.234 --> 24:48.567
-Davis will be joining us this evening.
-We're looking fonIvard to meeting him.

24:48.696 --> 24:51.654
-And to hearing you play.
-Great.

24:51.741 --> 24:52.901
Tonight is your band?

24:52.992 --> 24:56.905
No, tonight is the private party.
It's just gonna be violin and piano.

24:57.872 --> 24:59.112
What is the repertoire?

25:00.416 --> 25:03.408
Great American Songbook, some originals.

25:03.503 --> 25:05.744
Nothing classical?

25:06.089 --> 25:07.169
(LAUGHS)

25:07.256 --> 25:11.374
What about that Elgar piece you used to play,
"Salut d'amour"?

25:11.678 --> 25:12.838
No?

25:12.929 --> 25:16.717
You know, we might do some Scott Joplin.
And there's a Gottschalk piece.

25:16.891 --> 25:18.756
Gottschalk? I'm not familiar with...

25:19.102 --> 25:23.095
He is the first important
early Louisiana composer.

25:24.857 --> 25:27.894
-l'm looking fonIvard to hearing your band.
-(WOMEN LAUGH)

25:28.027 --> 25:31.064
So we are Annie T. and Her Bayou Cadillac.

25:31.155 --> 25:32.770
(ALL LAUGH)

25:32.949 --> 25:37.534
It's kind of like
a roots swamp-rock/Cajun thing.

25:37.620 --> 25:39.235
Bayou Cadillac.

25:39.539 --> 25:41.621
I love it. (CHUCKLES)

25:41.749 --> 25:44.456
You know, the guys,
they all play multiple instruments.

25:44.877 --> 25:48.711
It's very cool.
The piano, accordion, guitar, fiddle...

25:48.798 --> 25:53.132
Sometime, you have to explain to me
the difference between a fiddle and a violin.

25:53.636 --> 25:57.379
Well, fiddle is vernacular music,
and violin is...

25:57.473 --> 26:00.215
-|s not vernacular?
-(LAUGHS)

26:02.645 --> 26:05.682
-So I've been writing songs. Yeah.
-Oh.

26:05.773 --> 26:07.388
And I've been singing.

26:07.483 --> 26:08.472
BOTH: Singing?

26:08.568 --> 26:09.933
Yeah. (LAUGHING)

26:10.027 --> 26:12.643
-I didn't know you could sing.
-I didn't either.

26:12.739 --> 26:15.572
It's just something
I've been working on down here.

26:15.658 --> 26:17.649
It has been quite an adventure, hasn't it?

26:18.786 --> 26:20.651
Yeah, yeah, it has.

26:20.788 --> 26:22.995
-Ready for a refill?
-No, thank you.

26:23.166 --> 26:27.330
You know, if you need something stronger,
it's never too early to start in New Orleans.

26:28.421 --> 26:30.662
-Well, when in Rome...
-(ANNIE LAUGHS)

26:30.965 --> 26:33.251
Brandy milk punch, please.

26:34.844 --> 26:36.050
ANNIE: Dad?

26:36.679 --> 26:37.885
Why not?

26:38.181 --> 26:40.968
You know what? Make it three.
(LAUGHS) Thanks.

26:41.058 --> 26:45.347
(CROWD CHATTERING)

26:52.361 --> 26:53.521
-Chief.
-Hey, Suber.

26:53.613 --> 26:54.602
-Glad to see you here.
-Yeah, baby.

26:54.697 --> 26:55.732
You, too.

26:55.823 --> 26:58.530
Hey, just trying to
keep the old man out of trouble.

26:58.618 --> 26:59.858
Why's everybody out here?

26:59.952 --> 27:02.910
They say the chambers are full.
They're not letting anyone else in.

27:02.997 --> 27:04.032
Not even press.

27:04.123 --> 27:05.704
The meeting was supposed to start at 10:00.

27:05.792 --> 27:08.283
They decided to
swear Jackie Clarkson in at 9:00.

27:10.922 --> 27:13.163
Fix is in. I knew it.

27:13.424 --> 27:15.085
You got a feeling for how it's gonna fall?

27:15.176 --> 27:18.134
Four-three, everybody's saying,
in favor of demolition.

27:18.221 --> 27:21.133
-Four white, three black.
-Afraid so.

27:21.265 --> 27:22.880
(SIGHS)

27:26.604 --> 27:28.970
TONI: Here's another one from St. Louis.

27:29.607 --> 27:31.689
(DIALING)

27:35.947 --> 27:37.437
WOMAN: Medical facilities.

27:37.532 --> 27:39.693
TONI: Hello.
Could I speak with Dr. Evans, please?

27:39.784 --> 27:41.649
-Who's calling?
-My name is Toni Bernette.

27:41.744 --> 27:44.110
I'm calling from New Orleans. I'm an attorney.

27:44.205 --> 27:48.164
And Iwould like to talk to Dr. Evans
about the work he did here post-Katrina.

27:48.251 --> 27:51.539
REPORTER: So why did you come
here today? What's your message?

27:51.629 --> 27:53.335
-(CROWD CHATTERING)
-WOMAN: Well, we came just to say that

27:53.422 --> 27:56.459
people can't come home
unless they have a place to live.

27:56.592 --> 27:59.800
And these buildings were not damaged
and they should not be torn down.

27:59.929 --> 28:01.669
REPORTER 2:
But what about the council members

28:01.764 --> 28:04.506
who say you'll have
better housing, new housing?

28:04.600 --> 28:07.137
WOMAN: We don't believe that.
We're pleased with what we have.

28:07.270 --> 28:10.808
MAN: From the projects to the streets!
CROWD: Nojustice, no peace!

28:10.898 --> 28:14.766
MAN: From the projects to the streets!
CROWD: Nojustice, no peace!

28:14.902 --> 28:19.020
MAN: From the projects to the streets!
CROWD: Nojustice, no peace!

28:19.448 --> 28:22.440
(MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING OVER STEREO)

28:28.416 --> 28:30.657
Another applicant in front.

28:30.751 --> 28:34.460
-Brunette, perky, petite?
-No. This one's for you.

28:42.889 --> 28:44.504
Bonnie!

28:44.599 --> 28:46.089
(LAUGHING)

28:46.183 --> 28:50.142
-Paul, what are you doing in New Orleans?
-Well, I heard you were hiring.

28:50.229 --> 28:53.016
-No, don't tease me. God!
-(LAUGHING)

28:53.107 --> 28:55.223
Come on, what brings you down here?

28:55.318 --> 28:59.231
-How's things with Brulard?
-Not so good. Not good at all.

28:59.322 --> 29:02.359
-Really? Has he been listening to your fish?
-(LAUGHS) If only.

29:02.450 --> 29:04.816
That fuckin' maniac
threw a plate of risotto at me.

29:05.202 --> 29:06.533
-No.
-Yeah.

29:06.621 --> 29:08.111
But he didn't throw it, actually. He pressed.

29:08.205 --> 29:13.165
He pressed a plate of risotto up against
what I would call my nether regions.

29:13.336 --> 29:17.329
-Did that hurt?
-Well, it was warm, but not in a good way.

29:17.465 --> 29:20.252
So, you know, being a gentleman of leisure,
I thought I'd come down here

29:20.343 --> 29:22.459
and see what the big noise was
about this place you're opening up.

29:22.553 --> 29:23.542
Are you serious?

29:23.638 --> 29:25.924
Yeah, maybe start
a sweet segue into southern living.

29:26.015 --> 29:27.846
Would you really wanna work here?

29:28.142 --> 29:32.852
Come on, New Orleans is a little off the grid
for a big New York rising-star chef.

29:32.939 --> 29:35.681
Ijust wanna cook, and I think
this would be an awesome place to do it.

29:35.775 --> 29:38.812
Plus, you and I, a couple of Brulard
terror survivors, we understand each other.

29:38.903 --> 29:40.018
(LAUGHS)

29:40.112 --> 29:42.194
-If you want a job, I got one for you.
-Great.

29:42.281 --> 29:43.987
-When do I start?
-How about now?

29:44.075 --> 29:46.066
-I can't. Yeah, okay.
-Come on, you're late.

29:46.160 --> 29:47.661
-(LAUGHING)
-I'II show you the kitchen.

29:47.745 --> 29:52.535
(CHANTING) Let us in! Let us in!
Let us in! Let us in! Let us in!

29:52.625 --> 29:55.708
OFFICER:
You, back up. Get back from the gate.

29:55.836 --> 29:59.749
Let us in! Let us in! Let us in!

30:01.050 --> 30:05.714
(CHANTING CONTIN U ES)

30:08.975 --> 30:12.513
(SPRAYING)

30:12.603 --> 30:15.390
(WOMEN SCREAMING)

30:15.481 --> 30:17.722
-(ALL SHOUTING)
-(CAMERA CLICKING)

30:17.817 --> 30:19.603
OFFICER: Back up!

30:19.694 --> 30:20.979
(TASER CRACKLING)

30:21.070 --> 30:23.686
OFFICER 2: You're causing trouble again.
Put your hands behind your head.

30:23.781 --> 30:26.147
-(CAMERA CLICKS)
-(ALL SCREAMING)

30:26.242 --> 30:28.073
-(SPRAY HISSING)
(PEOPLE SHOUTING)

30:28.160 --> 30:29.536
WOMAN: You all right?

30:29.620 --> 30:31.781
MAN: Get him some water!
Get him some water!

30:31.872 --> 30:33.954
-(ALBERT COUGHING)
-Dad, you all right? Thank you, thank you.

30:35.126 --> 30:37.037
-(COUGHING)
-Dad, Dad.

30:37.169 --> 30:38.784
-(CHOKING)
-Hey, hey, hey.

30:38.879 --> 30:42.007
Wipe your eyes. Wipe your eyes.
Here, here, here, here.

30:42.091 --> 30:45.174
Looks like your ass is going back to jail,
Chief.

30:45.261 --> 30:47.843
This ain't gonna be
another Indian fuckin' photo op.

30:47.930 --> 30:50.046
Don't arrest his ass. Him either.

30:50.391 --> 30:52.256
Let's get outta here. Let's go.

30:52.601 --> 30:54.683
(CAMERAS CLICKING)
(ALBERT GROANS)

30:54.979 --> 30:57.220
-You all right?
-OFFICER: Back up!

30:57.314 --> 30:59.145
-(GROANING)
-Get out of here, man!

30:59.400 --> 31:00.685
(HELICOPTER HOVERING)

31:00.776 --> 31:02.357
-(COUGHING)
-You all right?

31:02.570 --> 31:04.276
Dad,Dad?

31:05.364 --> 31:11.325
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)
-(LOW CHATTER)

32:01.462 --> 32:03.373
(SCATTERED APPLAUSE)

32:03.464 --> 32:05.000
ANNIE: Thank you.

32:06.717 --> 32:08.332
So lovely.

32:08.636 --> 32:10.922
So, do you wanna do
All That and Then Some?

32:11.013 --> 32:14.176
Yeah, we can sneak some Fessnicity in
while no one's listening.

32:14.308 --> 32:16.424
-Exactly.
-(BOTH LAUGH)

32:16.519 --> 32:18.976
Two, three, four.

32:19.063 --> 32:21.270
(PLAYING LIVELY TUNE)

32:41.252 --> 32:45.040
The mambo
figures prominently in New Orleans piano.

32:45.381 --> 32:48.373
-Professor Longhair...
-I don't know him.

32:49.385 --> 32:52.593
It's the Cuba connection.

32:53.264 --> 32:56.882
Jelly Roll Morton called it the Spanish Tinge.

32:56.976 --> 33:02.141
There actually used to be an overnight ferry
between New Orleans and Havana, so...

33:02.231 --> 33:04.597
They say that a lot here.

33:04.692 --> 33:08.435
-What? Spanish Tinge?
-No. "There used to be."

33:08.529 --> 33:11.566
"There used to be this. There used to be that."

33:17.705 --> 33:19.661
CORNELL: So how's your Vietnamese, son?

33:19.790 --> 33:21.291
-(SONNY LAUGHS)
-And I don't mean pillow talk.

33:21.375 --> 33:23.161
(SPEAKS VIETNAMESE)
(CORNELL LAUGHS)

33:23.252 --> 33:24.833
Right back at you, motherfucker.

33:24.920 --> 33:26.330
(BOTH LAUGH)

33:26.422 --> 33:28.583
-So you're loving it.
-Yeah, I am.

33:29.216 --> 33:31.002
The work, too?

33:31.093 --> 33:34.301
Well, you know, I don't wanna
do it for the rest of my life, but...

33:35.306 --> 33:37.672
Damn, you got it bad.

33:38.225 --> 33:40.682
So you doing
Christmas dinner with the family?

33:40.978 --> 33:42.843
Igota gig.

33:42.980 --> 33:46.347
-She's not too happy about that.
-(LAUGHS) They never are.

33:46.442 --> 33:48.182
I was supposed to meet her grandmother.

33:48.277 --> 33:51.610
Son, that's an honor. No wonder she's pissed.

33:51.697 --> 33:54.814
-What's the gig?
-With Lightnin' at Mimi's.

33:56.368 --> 33:58.905
(TSKS) If I was you, I'd reconsider.

34:04.293 --> 34:06.875
(SINGING)
I see you lookin'

34:06.962 --> 34:08.668
WOMAN: Yeah, baby.
That's what I'm talking about.

34:08.756 --> 34:11.623
(SINGING)
Dig what you see

34:11.717 --> 34:15.209
I know what you're thinkin'

34:15.304 --> 34:18.717
There ain't much to me

34:18.807 --> 34:21.640
I'm no Beyonce

34:22.353 --> 34:24.844
But to my man, I am stacked

34:26.148 --> 34:29.606
'Cause nature supplied me, baby

34:29.777 --> 34:32.314
Not the T.J. Maxx

34:32.696 --> 34:36.484
I've got everything you need

34:38.327 --> 34:41.990
Said I'm gonna keep my man satisfied

34:42.081 --> 34:43.867
WOMAN: Tell 'em, baby.

34:49.171 --> 34:51.958
Merry fuckin' Christmas to me.

34:52.174 --> 34:55.086
Sounds good. Always liked Sharon.

34:55.261 --> 34:58.173
You just happened to be
in the neighborhood?

34:58.264 --> 35:02.928
In this neighborhood? Of course not.
Here to talk to you.

35:03.811 --> 35:06.848
-What are you drinking?
-Courvoisier.

35:07.898 --> 35:09.229
Let me see.

35:09.316 --> 35:12.353
There must be
a dirty glass around here somewhere.

35:13.862 --> 35:15.898
You know how to hold a grudge.

35:16.115 --> 35:17.946
I admire that.

35:18.742 --> 35:20.278
What do you want, Bernard?

35:20.369 --> 35:26.706
What I want is for my brother and his family
to break bread with me and mine at Christmas.

35:27.459 --> 35:29.620
We're dining out.

35:29.712 --> 35:31.043
For Christmas?

35:33.716 --> 35:35.377
Come to our house.

35:38.846 --> 35:41.212
(SIGHS) You know what?

35:42.891 --> 35:44.392
You're right.

35:45.102 --> 35:47.559
-Family and all that.
-Good.

35:49.565 --> 35:51.226
Y'all come here.

35:52.192 --> 35:53.898
Here?

35:53.986 --> 35:55.476
The bar?

35:55.612 --> 35:58.649
The bar will be closed. I'll cook.

35:58.824 --> 36:02.157
That's an interesting idea,
but Victorine's cooking.

36:02.244 --> 36:05.486
She don't cook. Might be catering it.

36:07.750 --> 36:09.331
What I thought.

36:09.877 --> 36:12.835
Well, I damn sure ain't going out there.

36:12.921 --> 36:14.331
LaDonna...

36:14.423 --> 36:19.008
See, I done made my last trip
to English Turn in this lifetime.

36:22.389 --> 36:25.973
REPORTER: Officers tasered two people
and arrested several more.

36:26.060 --> 36:29.848
As the violence spilled outside, council
members were determined to push on.

36:29.938 --> 36:33.146
Well, Lucy and Dennis, after
hours of debates and months of protests,

36:33.233 --> 36:34.894
the city council did decide unanimously

36:34.985 --> 36:38.273
to tear down
the big four housing projects in the city.

36:38.364 --> 36:41.606
-Unanimous, huh?
-REPORTER: ...after a morning of violence.

36:41.909 --> 36:45.151
Late this afternoon, Mayor Nagin
praised council members for their vote

36:45.245 --> 36:49.454
and what he called behind-the-scenes work
in the days leading up to the vote.

36:49.541 --> 36:51.042
Are you kidding me?

36:51.126 --> 36:53.742
There's only one way you can get to
seven-zero out of something like that,

36:53.837 --> 36:56.294
and it ain't by holding hands
and singing Kumbaya.

36:56.673 --> 36:58.129
What's Kumbaya?

36:58.217 --> 37:02.130
NAGIN: ...and worked their differences out,
came to a great place.

37:02.221 --> 37:06.885
And we stand here unified
as the entire council, the administration,

37:06.975 --> 37:09.307
and everybody's saying,
"This is a new day in New Orleans."

37:09.645 --> 37:14.105
I'm just saying, when everybody agrees,
there's something in it for everybody.

37:14.191 --> 37:15.271
REPORTER 2:...outside of City Hall.

37:15.359 --> 37:18.192
REPORTER: That's where our Bill Capo
spent the day. Bill, what can you tell us?

37:18.278 --> 37:20.564
BILL:
People who witnessed the scene outside

37:20.656 --> 37:24.490
the city council chambers
said it reminded them of the 1960s.

37:24.618 --> 37:27.075
(MUSIC PLAYING OVER STEREO)

37:27.162 --> 37:29.653
(KNOCKING AT DOOR)

37:35.587 --> 37:37.623
-Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas.

37:37.714 --> 37:39.124
They're almost ready. Come on in.

37:39.216 --> 37:40.672
I got my mama waiting in the car.

37:40.759 --> 37:42.875
-Hey, where's Larry?
-Hey.

37:43.011 --> 37:45.263
-The flu. Flat on his back in English Turn.
-Man, that's rough.

37:45.347 --> 37:46.427
(CHUCKLES)

37:46.515 --> 37:48.801
-Come on. I love you.
-I love you, too.

37:49.059 --> 37:50.174
Bye.

37:50.269 --> 37:51.759
-RANDALL: Thank you.
-DESIREE: You, too, darling.

37:51.854 --> 37:52.809
-Bye.
-ANTOINE: Bye.

37:52.896 --> 37:54.807
-Merry Christmas.
-Thank you. Merry Christmas.

37:55.524 --> 37:57.731
-DESIREE: Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas.

38:05.200 --> 38:08.658
-(LAUGHTER)
-That's not a rabbit. It was a squirrel.

38:08.745 --> 38:10.610
(LAUGHTER CONTIN U ES)

38:10.706 --> 38:12.196
RAMONA: Davis!

38:13.625 --> 38:14.876
(CLINKING)

38:16.044 --> 38:21.334
I would like to propose a toast
to Lost Highway's newest recording star.

38:21.425 --> 38:23.211
ALL: Hear, hear.

38:24.678 --> 38:26.134
Thank you.

38:26.221 --> 38:27.927
-We're proud of you, darling.
-Thank you.

38:28.140 --> 38:31.883
Well, it isn't the Deutsche Grammophon, but...

38:32.019 --> 38:34.476
-(LAUGHING)
-You're joining us tonight, right?

38:34.938 --> 38:36.223
-Yeah.
-I wouldn't miss it.

38:36.315 --> 38:39.432
It's so nice here this time of the year.
I had no idea.

38:39.568 --> 38:41.479
Camellias in bloom, 50 degrees.

38:41.570 --> 38:42.901
-We took the trolley.
-Yes.

38:42.988 --> 38:44.319
It's a streetcar, Daddy.

38:44.406 --> 38:46.738
You know, we haven't done that in years.

38:47.201 --> 38:49.362
When you live here,
you take certain things for granted.

38:49.453 --> 38:52.365
-Yes.
-This is a charming city, no doubt about it.

38:53.332 --> 38:54.947
We are worrying about the crime.

38:55.083 --> 38:56.744
Well, crime is a huge problem.

38:57.044 --> 38:59.831
-But there are reasons for optimism.
-Such as?

38:59.922 --> 39:03.585
RAMONA: Well, the city council just voted
to tear down the public housing projects.

39:03.675 --> 39:07.668
Mother, the projects have been closed
since the storm and we still have crime.

39:07.763 --> 39:11.551
In fact, it's worse.
So tearing down the projects isn't the answer.

39:11.934 --> 39:15.017
RAMONA: Well, the lberville is open,
and they're not tearing that down.

39:15.103 --> 39:16.513
"Eye-ber-vulle."

39:16.605 --> 39:19.597
I can't help if they can't pronounce
the name of where they live.

39:19.691 --> 39:20.680
I love it.

39:20.776 --> 39:25.190
The uptown matron telling the folks in
the hood how to pronounce where they live.

39:25.280 --> 39:27.111
I am not a matron.

39:27.199 --> 39:29.906
What is this Uberville?

39:30.285 --> 39:32.697
-It's a public housing project in Treme.
-THERESA: Yeah?

39:32.788 --> 39:34.244
Near where Davis and Annie live.

39:34.456 --> 39:35.866
You live next to a housing project?

39:35.958 --> 39:37.869
No, it's way on the other side
of Armstrong Park.

39:37.960 --> 39:42.670
You know, it's another great example
of this city at war with its cultural essence.

39:42.756 --> 39:47.671
Davis, I would hardly call the demolition
of the projects a war on our cultural essence.

39:47.803 --> 39:49.168
What? It's nothing less.

39:49.263 --> 39:51.925
All the great musicians
to come out of the projects...

39:52.015 --> 39:58.181
Germaine Bazzle, Willie Tee, Earl Turbinton,
The Neville Brothers, Mr. Google Eyes.

39:58.272 --> 40:01.309
-I love Mr. Google Eyes!
-(LAUGHTER)

40:01.400 --> 40:02.640
I know you do, Dad.

40:02.734 --> 40:05.726
What about all the criminals
that come out of the projects?

40:05.821 --> 40:09.530
Yeah, what about all the criminals
that come out of your alma mater LSU?

40:09.658 --> 40:11.774
Davis has a point there, Roger.

40:11.952 --> 40:13.237
-Mimi.
-MIMI: Well, What?

40:13.328 --> 40:18.163
There's Edwin Edwards,
Billy Cannon, Gil Dozier, David Duke.

40:18.250 --> 40:21.663
But the question
is whether where Annie lives is safe now.

40:21.795 --> 40:23.160
-Yes.
-No.

40:25.632 --> 40:28.169
-(SIGHS)
-Could somebody pass the oyster dressing?

40:29.011 --> 40:32.094
ALBERT: That's some spread.
Gumbo and crab soup.

40:32.848 --> 40:35.965
Stuffed mirlitons and stuffed peppers.

40:36.059 --> 40:38.311
-Turkey and roast pork.
-Thank you.

40:38.395 --> 40:42.138
Now sweet potato pie and pecan pie, too.

40:43.150 --> 40:45.687
-(CHUCKLES)
-Well, we all get together so seldom,

40:45.777 --> 40:48.189
we just wanted to be sure
you had all your favorites.

40:48.905 --> 40:52.193
-All my favorites?
-All your holiday favorites.

40:53.201 --> 40:55.032
In one meal?

41:02.461 --> 41:05.874
This is not my last Christmas dinner.

41:06.048 --> 41:09.415
-Next year, I'll cook. Understood?
-We got it.

41:19.811 --> 41:24.646
Well, I'm just grateful that neither of you two
got seriously hurt the other day.

41:24.733 --> 41:26.894
You think pepper spray is not serious?

41:27.027 --> 41:30.144
-My eyes still sting.
-Daddy, you know what I mean.

41:30.238 --> 41:31.978
-Or arrested.
-Yeah, you're right.

41:32.074 --> 41:34.315
ALBERT: That was foolish.
I shouldn't have gone down there.

41:34.618 --> 41:36.779
It was a done deal, that vote.

41:36.870 --> 41:39.361
That was just for show. Sorry I was part of it.

41:39.456 --> 41:41.913
DAVINA:
You stood up for what you believed in.

41:42.000 --> 41:44.241
You fought the good fight.

41:44.670 --> 41:47.503
Yeah, well, somebody else can fight that fight.

41:48.507 --> 41:49.917
I'm tired.

42:01.061 --> 42:02.722
(CHATTER)

42:02.813 --> 42:05.350
NIKOLICH: I says, "Could,
you know, you do a holiday tie?"

42:05.440 --> 42:09.649
And I says to Martin,
"Colson's tie looks like a nine-volt battery."

42:09.820 --> 42:11.401
Silent night.

42:11.488 --> 42:12.944
Let's hope.

42:13.031 --> 42:15.773
-Who else is on?
-Silby and Cappell.

42:15.867 --> 42:18.449
Well, I see Cappell. Where's Silby?

42:19.287 --> 42:21.118
Hey, Cappell.

42:21.289 --> 42:23.200
-Where's Silby?
-Errand.

42:24.084 --> 42:26.370
You read the 24s yet?

42:26.461 --> 42:28.873
Halliday caught a doozy last night.

42:28.964 --> 42:31.797
A man shot
on the corner of Liberty and Valence.

42:34.469 --> 42:35.675
You don't get it, do you?

42:35.887 --> 42:37.423
I get it.

42:38.140 --> 42:42.179
(IMITATES JOHN WAYNE)
"Hey, pilgrim. Here's your popgun."

42:42.394 --> 42:43.975
(LAUGHS)

43:04.624 --> 43:06.831
Kay. It's me.

43:09.212 --> 43:11.168
Thanks. Merry Christmas.

43:16.553 --> 43:18.509
Merry Christmas, kiddo.

43:18.638 --> 43:21.300
You and your brother having a good day?

43:21.391 --> 43:23.097
Yeah.

43:24.227 --> 43:26.388
You get the present I sent you?

43:27.689 --> 43:31.056
In fact, I'm wearing it right now.

43:34.362 --> 43:36.819
WAITER: Everything okay?
MAN: Fine, thank you.

43:36.948 --> 43:40.281
-Well, Jen, everything good for you?
-WOMAN: Lovely, Steve.

43:40.368 --> 43:41.448
Nice consomme.

43:41.536 --> 43:43.948
SOFIA: What's wrong?
TONI: Nothing.

43:45.040 --> 43:47.782
I was just thinking since Daddy...

43:49.377 --> 43:54.041
Maybe we need a change
from our old traditions, you know?

43:55.050 --> 43:56.881
Like What? This?

44:01.681 --> 44:03.842
Let's have dinner at home next Christmas.

44:05.352 --> 44:07.388
Sure, if I'm home from school.

44:07.479 --> 44:09.561
Why wouldn't you be?

44:10.899 --> 44:12.355
I don't know.

44:25.330 --> 44:28.413
Well, is there anything else
you'd like to do differently?

44:29.417 --> 44:31.078
I don't know.

44:34.339 --> 44:36.796
Maybe we could
go look at the Christmas lights.

44:36.883 --> 44:37.998
(LAUGHS)

44:38.093 --> 44:40.049
Al Copeland's?

44:40.262 --> 44:43.925
Dad used to say that house
was a garish display of new wealth.

44:44.057 --> 44:45.422
He was right.

44:45.684 --> 44:47.595
It doesn't make it any less...

44:47.686 --> 44:49.642
-Awesome.
-Awesome.

44:50.438 --> 44:54.272
So, next year, Al Copeland's Christmas lights.

44:55.610 --> 44:56.816
Cool.

44:59.614 --> 45:01.696
We can go tomorrow night if you want.

45:02.409 --> 45:03.990
No date?

45:04.286 --> 45:08.279
I was supposed to hang out with
Scottie and some friends, but whatever.

45:09.165 --> 45:11.201
Or you could invite them to come along.

45:12.002 --> 45:13.412
Please.

45:13.962 --> 45:15.918
Seriously. Why not?

45:18.133 --> 45:19.748
(LAUGHS)

45:20.760 --> 45:23.137
(PLAYING FAST-PACED TUNE)

45:32.314 --> 45:34.555
(SINGING)
You brought the wind, you brought the rain

45:34.649 --> 45:36.810
Katrina, you've caused me pain

45:36.985 --> 45:38.941
Katrina, you've caused me pain

45:39.029 --> 45:41.111
I need water and I need bread

45:41.197 --> 45:43.153
I need Katrina out of my bed

45:43.283 --> 45:46.320
Katrina, get out of my bed

46:01.176 --> 46:03.007
(SONG ENDS)

46:03.178 --> 46:06.170
(CROWD CHEERING)

46:07.223 --> 46:09.088
ANNIE: Thank you.

46:09.517 --> 46:11.769
Thank you so much.

46:14.397 --> 46:19.391
So I was supposed to be
in Vienna by now, or Philadelphia.

46:19.694 --> 46:24.404
Yeah, playing with a high-class "sympathy"
orchestra, as Professor Longhair would say.

46:24.491 --> 46:26.027
(CROWD CHUCKLES)

46:26.326 --> 46:29.318
But instead, I took a big detour in my life.

46:29.704 --> 46:33.117
And this Christmas,
I convinced my mom and dad...

46:33.208 --> 46:34.914
(CROWD CHEERING)
(ANNIE LAUGHS)

46:35.001 --> 46:38.289
...to come down to New Orleans,
see what I've been up to.

46:38.380 --> 46:41.042
So I hope this next song helps to explain.

46:41.257 --> 46:43.509
(CROWD CHEERING)

46:43.885 --> 46:46.171
(PLAYING LIVELY TUNE)

46:47.389 --> 46:49.550
(SINGING)
I'm a family girl

46:50.558 --> 46:52.890
I wasn't born to roam

46:52.978 --> 46:57.187
But seems like every Christmas
finds me farther from my home

46:57.524 --> 46:59.936
I love singin' my song

47:00.026 --> 47:02.483
But it gets me down

47:02.612 --> 47:04.648
To hang my stocking in some hotel

47:04.739 --> 47:06.479
When the fat man comes to town

47:06.574 --> 47:09.316
But it's all right

47:09.411 --> 47:11.993
It's gonna be okay

47:12.080 --> 47:14.162
'Cause this year I'll be home

47:14.249 --> 47:16.786
Come Louisiana Christmas day

47:16.876 --> 47:18.867
Oh, now, Mama

47:18.962 --> 47:21.328
I'm gonna find a way

47:21.423 --> 47:23.505
Your little girl's coming on home

47:23.591 --> 47:25.456
For Louisiana Christmas day

47:26.761 --> 47:29.594
(MUFFLED MUSIC PLAYING)

47:29.764 --> 47:31.755
(CHATTER)

47:38.940 --> 47:39.975
LEO: Hey.

47:42.485 --> 47:43.565
SONNY: Already?

47:43.653 --> 47:45.439
I thought we had another 10 minutes.

47:46.072 --> 47:47.357
A little Christmas cheer?

47:48.450 --> 47:49.610
Nah, I'm cool.

47:49.826 --> 47:51.032
We'll make it snow.

47:52.120 --> 47:53.610
Nah, I'm good.

47:54.914 --> 47:56.245
All right.

48:09.345 --> 48:11.597
(SINGING) All right
-CROWD: All right

48:11.681 --> 48:14.172
-Gonna be okay
-Gonna be okay

48:14.267 --> 48:16.724
-Yeah, I'll be home
-l'll be home

48:16.811 --> 48:18.347
On Louisiana Christmas day

48:18.480 --> 48:21.096
-Oh, now, Mama
-Mama

48:21.191 --> 48:23.773
-I'm gonna find a way
-We're gonna find a way

48:23.860 --> 48:26.192
-Yeah, I'll be home
-l'll be home

48:26.279 --> 48:27.940
For Louisiana Christmas day

48:28.031 --> 48:30.647
-Oh, it's gonna be all right
-Gonna be all right

48:30.742 --> 48:32.903
-Gonna be okay
-Gonna be okay

48:32.994 --> 48:34.404
(POLICE RADIO CHATTER)

48:34.496 --> 48:37.203
NIKOLICH: I'm not saying it's right,
but what did she expect?

48:37.290 --> 48:38.996
Families are out of bounds.

48:39.084 --> 48:42.997
I'm just saying, you stick your hand
in the beehive, you're gonna get stung.

48:43.963 --> 48:45.919
Wilson's off the reservation.

48:46.007 --> 48:47.292
Must be.

48:47.383 --> 48:50.125
He had to know, right? That she'd react.

48:50.720 --> 48:52.927
She went straight to Grayson.

48:53.431 --> 48:56.093
-Grayson hates her.
-She's got balls.

48:56.184 --> 48:57.845
(LAUGHS) Yeah.

48:58.186 --> 48:59.175
Oh!

49:02.524 --> 49:04.355
-Thanks forjoining us.
-Yeah, fuck you.

49:04.442 --> 49:06.603
TERRY:
Silby, where the hell have you been?

49:07.362 --> 49:08.898
Pharmacy.

49:08.988 --> 49:11.570
Had to pick up
a couple of prescriptions for my wife.

49:11.658 --> 49:12.989
Detective,

49:13.910 --> 49:17.073
this is the first time I've seen your face
since your shift started.

49:17.163 --> 49:19.996
Where the fuck is your pharmacy?
Baton Rouge?

49:20.750 --> 49:22.615
Didn't you get my message?

49:22.710 --> 49:24.746
I was following up with an eyewitness.

49:24.838 --> 49:26.453
On Christmas day?

49:26.548 --> 49:28.129
She doesn't live in town anymore.

49:28.216 --> 49:29.831
Only came back for the holiday.

49:29.926 --> 49:32.133
-Said, "Now or never."
-Silby.

49:34.681 --> 49:36.637
We'll finish this later.

49:37.433 --> 49:39.139
(TRAIN HORN BLARING)

49:44.941 --> 49:47.648
LEO: Out of the darkness and into the light.

49:50.071 --> 49:52.187
Get home safe, boys.

49:52.282 --> 49:54.068
Thanks, Miss JoAnn.

49:56.244 --> 49:58.610
-You coming?
-Nah, I'm done.

49:59.080 --> 50:00.866
That was epic, man.

50:02.834 --> 50:04.745
Glad to have you back.

50:09.007 --> 50:11.214
-Watch out, crackhead.
-Fuck.

50:20.560 --> 50:22.551
(MUSIC BLARING OVER STEREO)

50:35.783 --> 50:37.284
Coming in hot.

50:42.373 --> 50:44.489
-MAN: Looking good.
-PAUL: Scallops are happy.

50:59.057 --> 51:01.298
Getting there. Getting there.

51:06.356 --> 51:08.563
WILL: We got a state-of-the-art
recording studio,

51:08.650 --> 51:10.982
classroom and exhibition space,

51:11.653 --> 51:14.065
maybe a cafe, art gallery.

51:14.155 --> 51:16.817
-What about the fence?
-The fence?

51:18.159 --> 51:20.525
The fence around Armstrong Park.

51:21.746 --> 51:23.611
That cuts it off from the rest of the Treme.

51:23.706 --> 51:26.163
-The neighborhood hates it.
-Why?

51:27.335 --> 51:28.791
It's an insult.

51:28.878 --> 51:31.585
Keeps the kids out,
the little Louis Armstrongs.

51:31.673 --> 51:33.163
Tells them they're not wanted.

51:35.134 --> 51:38.342
We'll look into what's involved
in taking it down.

51:39.013 --> 51:41.129
Some of us were involved
in the Jazz Center project

51:41.224 --> 51:43.215
that would have been constructed
where city hall is now.

51:43.434 --> 51:45.095
Why did that fall through?

51:45.186 --> 51:47.472
The mayor and some of the partners
didn't see eye to eye.

51:47.939 --> 51:50.681
But the silver lining is we're better off.

51:50.775 --> 51:53.187
The municipal auditorium
is an historic building.

51:53.278 --> 51:56.395
The financing is there
and we're in Louis Armstrong Park.

51:56.864 --> 51:59.241
Congo Square, the root of it all.

52:00.326 --> 52:02.408
Bringing back Congo Square would be huge.

52:02.495 --> 52:05.077
Look, we want an artist at the table,

52:05.540 --> 52:07.781
someone who knows the community.

52:07.875 --> 52:09.786
We'd like your father to be on board as well.

52:09.877 --> 52:12.710
We want the whole spectrum
of authentic New Orleans culture.

52:12.797 --> 52:15.504
The real deal,
that's the experience people want.

52:17.885 --> 52:20.718
-Big Chiefs where Rex and Comus meet?
-(ALL LAUGH)

52:21.014 --> 52:22.754
It's a new day, Delmond.

52:22.849 --> 52:24.089
Why not?

52:26.436 --> 52:27.972
HOWARD: I don't know.

52:28.062 --> 52:29.347
-I can't make up my mind.
-(BELL DINGS)

52:30.106 --> 52:31.971
I'll tell you what, Chief, take it all home.

52:32.066 --> 52:34.557
-Bring back what you don't want.
-Thank you. That'll work.

52:34.652 --> 52:36.608
It don't matter what color you choose anyway.

52:36.696 --> 52:38.027
I'm gonna be the prettiest.

52:38.114 --> 52:40.196
You mean you're gonna be
the prettiest downtown, huh?

52:40.283 --> 52:42.490
(BOTH LAUGH)

52:43.077 --> 52:45.614
Alan, Taylor, I want you to meet Miss Ana.

52:45.705 --> 52:47.821
-Hello.
-Miss Helen, and Chief Howard.

52:47.915 --> 52:49.200
Hey, how y'all doing, baby?

52:49.292 --> 52:50.702
-Good.
-HOWARD: Let me get up out of here.

52:50.793 --> 52:52.749
Miss Helen, I'm gonna
bring back what I don't use

52:52.837 --> 52:54.702
so you can sell it to this fella here.

52:54.797 --> 52:56.958
(MEN CHUCKLE)

52:57.175 --> 52:58.915
Chief, what can I do for you?

52:59.010 --> 53:00.170
You know what I need?

53:00.261 --> 53:03.173
I need some of those
teardrop sew-on acrylics you carry,

53:03.264 --> 53:04.674
light green, you know.

53:04.766 --> 53:05.881
Both sides, now.

53:06.517 --> 53:07.848
And I ordered some plumes.

53:07.935 --> 53:10.426
-I wanna check on them, too.
-(BELL DINGS)

53:10.772 --> 53:11.761
Oh!

53:12.815 --> 53:14.601
-Chief Doucette.
-What's up, brother?

53:16.277 --> 53:18.563
-Happy holidays.
-That was fast.

53:23.951 --> 53:25.452
This is it?

53:25.536 --> 53:28.903
Playing without a permit, public intoxication,

53:28.998 --> 53:30.283
speeding ticket.

53:31.626 --> 53:34.459
Pretty law-abiding for a street musician.

53:36.547 --> 53:38.583
Is he really 27?

53:44.514 --> 53:46.800
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

53:48.601 --> 53:52.344
Shrimp Clemenceau with
roasted new potatoes, mushrooms,

53:52.522 --> 53:55.514
sugar snap peas,
and Becnel's Meyer lemon butter.

53:55.608 --> 53:57.018
Thank you, Chef.

54:09.789 --> 54:12.075
-This is good.
-What did I tell you?

54:14.419 --> 54:16.080
It's delicious, Tim.

54:20.341 --> 54:22.332
(BAND PLAYING)

54:35.857 --> 54:39.520
I couldn't believe it was seven-zero,
even with all that protest.

54:40.611 --> 54:43.273
We're maturing as a community.

54:43.364 --> 54:46.197
The protestors you saw
were the last gasp of a dying mentality.

54:46.284 --> 54:48.525
We finally have the Philistines on the run.

54:52.457 --> 54:54.288
Well, thanks for coming out.

54:54.375 --> 54:56.331
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

54:56.419 --> 54:59.377
Here's to a healthy and prosperous new year.

55:03.718 --> 55:07.176
This public housing thing,
the redevelopment,

55:07.263 --> 55:08.719
obviously it's gonna be huge.

55:08.806 --> 55:10.842
It has the potential to transform the city.

55:13.269 --> 55:15.510
That thing we were worried about,

55:15.605 --> 55:18.142
there hasn't been any repercussions.

55:18.733 --> 55:21.349
I feel I've put in my time,

55:21.444 --> 55:23.184
learned the lay of the land, so to speak.

55:24.447 --> 55:28.781
I like you, Nelson, and you seemed
to have weathered that storm, but...

55:29.410 --> 55:33.073
It's not clear to me what you as an outsider
can bring to this venture.

55:49.347 --> 55:52.259
Bacon-wrapped Louisiana pork loin
with smothered greens,

55:52.350 --> 55:55.592
roasted butternut squash,
and Steen's Cane Syrup jus.

56:13.246 --> 56:14.611
Delicious.

56:16.165 --> 56:18.542
You know what makes this dish really great?

56:18.626 --> 56:20.207
Steen's Cane Syrup.

56:20.294 --> 56:22.546
Costs half as much as Vermont Maple Syrup.

56:22.630 --> 56:25.747
But you put those words
on a menu in this town and people go crazy,

56:25.841 --> 56:27.217
tourists and locals alike.

56:27.301 --> 56:28.882
This dish is a moneymaker.

56:28.970 --> 56:30.676
(CHUCKLES)

56:34.225 --> 56:36.216
(WATER RUNNING)

56:39.230 --> 56:41.095
-Are you ready?
-Ready.

56:41.190 --> 56:43.431
-(SMASHING)
-The hell was that?

56:45.945 --> 56:47.981
-(KNOCKING AT DOOR)
-It's a cop.

56:54.662 --> 56:56.277
-Officer.
-Evening, ma'am.

56:56.831 --> 56:59.117
Is that your car?

57:03.504 --> 57:06.337
lwasjust driving by and noticed
someone smashed your windshield.

57:09.343 --> 57:11.834
Sorry to be the bearer of bad news.

57:12.513 --> 57:14.253
Enjoy your evening.

57:26.319 --> 57:28.105
(ENGINE STARTS)
